Our Theorem 1 is applicable to any base federated learning algorithm, any lower bound py of py and any upper bound pz of pz that satisfy (7). When the lower bound py and upper bound pz are estimated more accurately, i.e., py and pz are respectively closer to py and pz, our certiï¬ed security level may be larger. The following theorem shows that our derived certiï¬ed security level is tight, i.e., when no assumptions on the base federated learning algorithm are made, it is impossible to derive a certiï¬ed security level that is larger than ours for the given probability bounds py and pz.
Theorem 2. Suppose py + pz â‰¤ 1. For any C satisfying |C âˆ’ C| > mâˆ—, i.e., at least mâˆ— + 1 clients are malicious, there exists a base federated learning algorithm f âˆ— that satisï¬es (7) but F (C , x) = y or there exist ties.

Given a test set D, Algorithm 1 shows our algorithm to
compute the predicted labels and certiï¬ed security levels for
all test inputs in D. The function SAMPLE&TRAIN randomly
samples N groups with k clients and trains N global models
using the base federated learning algorithm f . We use 1 âˆ’ pyË†t as an upper bound for pzË†t because we want to limit the probability of incorrect bound pairs (pzË†t , pyË†t ) within Î±/|D|. Given the probability bounds pyË†t and pzË†t for a test input xt, the function SEARCHLEVEL ï¬nds the certiï¬ed security level mË† âˆ—t via ï¬nding the largest integer m that satisï¬es (6). For example, SEARCHLEVEL can simply start m from 0 and iteratively increase it by one until ï¬nding mË† âˆ—t .
In Algorithm 1, since we estimate the lower bound pyË†t using the Clopper-Pearson method, there is a probability that
the estimated lower bound is incorrect, i.e., pyË†t > pyË†t . When the lower bound is estimated incorrectly for a test input xt, the certiï¬ed security level mË† âˆ—t output by Algorithm 1 for xt may also be incorrect, i.e., there may exist an C such that |C âˆ’ C| â‰¤ mË† âˆ—t but F (C , xt) = yË†t. In other words, our Algorithm 1 has probabilistic guarantees for its output certiï¬ed
security levels. However, in the following theorem, we prove
the probability that Algorithm 1 returns an incorrect certiï¬ed
security level for at least one test input is at most Î±.

Theorem 3. The probability that Algorithm 1 returns an incorrect certiï¬ed security level for at least one testing example in D is bounded by Î±, which is equivalent to:

