B. Experimental Results
1) Certiï¬ed Accuracy: We ï¬rst show results on certiï¬ed accuracy.
Comparing FLCert with single-global-model and CRFL: We compare the two variants of FLCert with two baselines, i.e., single-global-model FL and CRFL [31]. For CRFL, we use their default parameter settings, i.e., the clipping threshold Ï = 15, standard deviation Ïƒ = 0.01, and sample size M = 1, 000. Figure 3 shows the results on all ï¬ve datasets, where FedAvg is the base FL algorithm. We observe that when there are no malicious clients (i.e., m = 0), single-global-model FedAvg and CRFL have larger certiï¬ed accuracy than FLCert. However, single-global-model FedAvg and CRFL have 0 certiï¬ed accuracy when just one client is malicious. This is because a single malicious client can arbitrarily manipulate the global model learnt by FedAvg [32], reducing the certiï¬ed accuracy of single-globalmodel FedAvg to 0, and its local training data, reducing the certiï¬ed accuracy of CRFL to 0.
Moreover, we notice that there is a trade-off between the two variants of FLCert for MNIST-0.1, MNIST-0.5, and Reddit, where N is large. Speciï¬cally, when m is small, FLCert-D has higher certiï¬ed accuracy. This is because in FLCert-P, we estimate the label probabilities, which reduces the gap between the largest and the second largest label probabilities. On the contrary, when m is large, FLCert-P achieves higher certiï¬ed accuracy, which is because FLCert-P can naturally certify more malicious clients than FLCert-D in the extreme cases if we compare Equation 6 with Equation 12. However, FLCert-P cannot certify any malicious client on CIFAR-10 and HAR. This is because the number of groups N is small for these two datasets, e.g., N = 15 for HAR, which results in inaccurate estimation of label probabilities. A possible solution is to design probability estimation methods that are more accurate with a small number of samples. We also found that if we increase N to 500 while keeping k = 2, the certiï¬ed accuracy of FLCert-P is still larger than 0 when up to 8 out of 30 clients are malicious for HAR. However, FLCert-P incurs a much larger communication/computation overhead than FLCert-D in such scenario.
N achieves a trade-off between accuracy and provable security: We explore the impact of the number of groups N on FLCert. Figure 4 shows the results. We observe that N controls a trade-off between accuracy under no attacks

